;\\n        IllegalStateException wrapper = new IllegalStateException(\\\"startup failed\\\", rootCause);\\n\\n        String stackTrace = ExceptionUtil.printStackTrace(wrapper, 0, true, true);\\n\\n        assertThat(stackTrace)\\n                .contains(\\\"java.lang.IllegalStateException: startup failed\\\")\\n                .contains(\\\"rethrown from\\\")\\n                .contains(\\\"java.lang.IllegalArgumentException: configuration value is missing\\\");\\n    }\\n}\\n\"}], \"isError\": false, \"timestamp\": 1777739096363}]}\n783:[thinking] I think tests shouldn't resolve nonexistent versions. For instance, 4.1.5-dev from the source repo isn't a valid Maven version. But the test has to use a library version, right? Maybe I could add a repository to help with this. I also need to check if the artifact is available in my local Maven setup. I want to ensure everything lines up for proper functionality!\n789:[recv] {\"type\": \"message_end\", \"message\": {\"role\": \"assistant\", \"content\": [{\"type\": \"thinking\", \"thinking\": \"**Evaluating library versions**\\n\\nI think tests shouldn't resolve nonexistent versions. For instance, 4.1.5-dev from the source repo isn't a valid Maven version. But the test has to use a library version, right? Maybe I could add a repository to help with this. I also need to check if the artifact is available in my local Maven setup. I want to ensure everything lines up for proper functionality!\", \"thinkingSignature\": \"{\\\"id\\\":\\\"rs_0cc59499cf708cf10169f62559b26881a3846dde4c72cae981\\\",\\\"type\\\":\\\"reasoning\\\",\\\"encrypted_content\\\":\\\"gAAAAABp9iVbaDWWYqDuhMAhgQ_1qGeNzI3FSCOadMRunQJaF6EIjnA1C557wTJSLo3Ua7FF88lMLTANB3yPshtxTlPktbIzLZCO2aBG5Rjq-R2U2YHrCT4-82xHuwkjtDXFnVP5gljzpEtL360qYvm9XFacYKIiHIO42ttop7rRU_gAmfYMWNhjIxdxzC7Pwz9DjKCYHNnXI8LJG4swqpk9V88Gh6pimbBevwoHKzzttiBfErmMe2Ek-5X5vs6Jox9uUj-D_tnMwg4n9GcTR_ACLYfjue5Ku6TCHif54QUteFf5PVwc2qztka9QdL43IAC5ukcwgRabipgB66gMD7QnBsAqimC2r9yYDj5gRA2jX7f_ER57uTx